I was able to reproduce this just by using Go's standard JSON encoder:

``` go
package main

import (
    "encoding/json"
    "log"
    "os"
)

type Some struct {
    Url string `json:"login"`
}

func main() {
    r := &Some{"https://example.com/inbox&test=totot"}
    if err := json.NewEncoder(os.Stdout).Encode(r); err != nil {
        log.Fatal(err)
    }
}
```

Output:

```
[andrew@Liger martini] go run 195-json.go 
{"login":"https://example.com/inbox\u0026test=totot"}
```

It appears this is an undocumented feature of the `encoding/json` package: http://golang.org/src/pkg/encoding/json/encode.go#L815 --- it doesn't explicitly mention `&`, but it's included in line 797.

As far as I can tell, this is working as intended. The JSON spec allows for unicode characters to be escaped, so any conforming decoder should be able to read your JSON without any problems.

