. I think thing here is to realize that the keys of `martini.Params` are taken straight from the named capture groups of the regex. As @mvader pointed out, the full regex ends up looking something like `(?P<id>[^/#?]+)([0-9]+)`. That is, `:name` is syntactic sugar for "bind a single piece of a URL to the name `name`."

So to get the behavior you want, just introduce the named capture directly. Here's a full working example:

``` go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "log"

    "github.com/go-martini/martini"
)

func main() {
    m := martini.Classic()
    m.Get("/test/(?P<id>[0-9]+)", func(p martini.Params) string {
        return fmt.Sprintf("ID %s", p["id"])
    })
    m.Run()
}
```
. I strongly disagree that everything should be case insensitive. Some might want to maintain the property that there is exactly one URL for a page. (I'm not saying everyone _should_ do this all the time, but that it's a reasonable use case.)

I don't have particularly strong feelings about adding a case insensitive option to the public API, but I lean toward not. Consider that you could just wrap a `ClassicMartini` and provide case insensitivity yourself without cluttering up your routes:

``` go
package main

import (
    "fmt"

    "github.com/codegangsta/martini"
)

type ClassicInsensitive struct {
    *martini.ClassicMartini
}

func (c ClassicInsensitive) Get(s string, hs ...martini.Handler) martini.Route {
    return c.Router.Get("(?i)" + s, hs...)
}

func main() {
    m := ClassicInsensitive{martini.Classic()}
    m.Get("/hello/:name", func(p martini.Params) string {
        return fmt.Sprintf("Hello %s", p["name"])
    })
    m.Run()
}
```

Of course, you'd have to wrap the other router methods too, but you get the idea.
